revision.text:
[[File:Checklist of North American birds.pdf|thumb|right|The first edition of the ''AOU Checklist of North American Birds''|page=7]]
{{italic title}}
The '''''AOS Checklist of North American Birds''''' is a checklist of the bird species found in [[North America|North]] and [[Middle America (Americas)|Middle America]] which is now maintained by the [[American Ornithological Society]] (AOS). The checklist was originally published by the AOS's predecessor, the American Ornithologists' Union (AOU). The Union merged with the [[Cooper Ornithological Society]] in 2016 to form the American Ornithological Society.<ref>{{ cite web | title=AOU History | url=http://www.americanornithology.org/content/aou-history | publisher=American Ornithological Society | accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref> The checklist was first published in 1886;<ref>{{Cite book | year=1886 | title=The Code of Nomenclature and Check-list of North American Birds Adopted by the American Ornithologists' Union | publisher =American Ornithologists' Union | place=New York | doi=10.5962/bhl.title.1538 | doi-access=free }}</ref> the seventh edition of the checklist was published in 1998<ref>{{cite book |title=Checklist of North American Birds |year=1998 |publisher=American Ornithologists' Union |location=New York, US |isbn=1-891276-00-X }}</ref> and is now updated every year by an [[Open access journal|open-access]] article published in the ''[[The Ibis|Ibis]]''.<ref name=checklist>{{cite web | title=Checklist of North and Middle American Birds | publisher=American Ornithological Society | url=http://www.americanornithology.org/content/checklist-north-and-middle-american-birds | accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref> Seven editions and 54 supplements (minor updates) have been published in the last 127 years. According to [[Joel Asaph Allen]], the Codes of Nomenclature set out in the first edition of the Checklist "later became the basis of the [[International Code of Zoological Nomenclature]], framed on essentially the same lines and departing from it in no essential respect, except in point of brevity, through omission of adequate illustrations of the rules, and thereby rendering necessary the issuance of official 'Opinions' to clear up obscure points."<ref>{{cite book |last=Allen |first=Joel Asaph |year=1916 | title=Autobiographical notes and a bibliography of the scientific publications of Joel Asaph Allen | page=40 | publisher=[[American Museum of Natural History]] |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/44824381 |doi=10.5962/bhl.title.82666 | doi-access=free}}</ref>

The current version of the checklist is available online from the website of the American Ornithological Society.<ref name=checklist/> The list is updated regularly by the AOS's North American Classification Committee (NACC), which considers proposals related to [[Biological classification|classification]] and [[Binomial nomenclature|nomenclature]].<ref>{{ cite web | title=Checklist of North and Middle American Birds: Current Proposals | url=http://checklist.aou.org/nacc/proposals/current_proposals.html | publisher=American Ornithological Society | accessdate=22 January 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{ cite web | title=Checklist of North and Middle American Birds: Previous Proposals | url=http://checklist.aou.org/nacc/proposals/prior_proposals.html | publisher=American Ornithological Society | accessdate=22 January 2017 }}</ref>

