'''Green leaf volatiles''' (commonly abbreviated as '''GLV''') are [[Volatile organic compound|volatile organic compounds]] that are released when plants suffer tissue damage. Specifically, they include [[Aldehyde|aldehydes]], [[Ester|esters]], and [[Alcohol|alcohols]] of 6-carbon compounds released after wounding.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-11101536|title=Plants send SOS signal to insects|last=Gill|first=Victoria|date=2010-08-27|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-11-28|language=en-GB}}</ref> These compounds are very quickly produced and emitted, and are used by nearly every green plant.<ref name=":0" /> Plants constantly release GLVs, but un-stressed plants release them in much smaller amounts.<ref>{{Citation|last=Li|first=Tao|title=Neighbour Recognition Through Volatile-Mediated Interactions|date=2016|url=https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/978-3-319-33498-1_7|work=Signaling and Communication in Plants|pages=153–174|publisher=Springer International Publishing|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-319-33498-1_7|isbn=9783319334967|access-date=2018-11-28}}</ref> Some of these chemicals act as [[Signaling (telecommunications)|signaling]] compounds between either plants of the same species, of other species, or even vastly different lifeforms like insects. Some, although not necessarily all, of these chemicals act essentially as plant [[pheromones]].<sup>[[Green leaf volatiles#cite note-2|[12]]]</sup> GLVs also have antimicrobial properties to prevent infection at the site of injury.<ref name=":1" />
== Uses == GLVs are used in both plant-plant and plant-insect interactions. They usually serve as a warning signal of oncoming causes of tissue damage. When a plant is attacked, it emits GLVs into the environment through the air<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Scala|first=Alessandra|last2=Allmann|first2=Silke|last3=Mirabella|first3=Rossana|last4=Haring|first4=Michel A.|last5=Schuurink|first5=Robert C.|date=2013-08-30|title=Green Leaf Volatiles: A Plant’s Multifunctional Weapon against Herbivores and Pathogens|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3794753/|journal=International Journal of Molecular Sciences|volume=14|issue=9|pages=17781–17811|doi=10.3390/ijms140917781|issn=1422-0067|pmc=3794753|pmid=23999587}}</ref>. Undamaged neighboring plants perceive these GLV signals and activate the expression of genes related to the plants defense mechanisms<ref name=":1" />. This allows the plant emitting the GLVs and the neighboring plants to enter a primed state. In this primed state plants activate their defenses systems more quickly and in a stronger concentration<ref>{{Cite journal|last=ul Hassan|first=Muhammad Naeem|last2=Zainal|first2=Zamri|last3=Ismail|first3=Ismanizan|date=August 2015|title=Green leaf volatiles: biosynthesis, biological functions and their applications in biotechnology|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/25865366|journal=Plant Biotechnology Journal|volume=13|issue=6|pages=727–739|doi=10.1111/pbi.12368|issn=1467-7652|pmid=25865366}}</ref>. The amount of GLVs that a wounded plant emits is directly related to the severity of the injury, so the concentration of GLVs in the atmosphere and the frequency of exposure both play a role in neighboring plants successfully entering a primed state<ref name=":0" />.
In plant-insect interactions, GLVs are used as a form of defense. They alert [[predators]] to the locations of [[Herbivore|herbivores]] that are preying on the plant and causing tissue damage. For example, a study done by Northwestern University found that [[Parasitoid wasp|parasitic wasps]] are more attracted to plants that are emitting GLVs due to wounding from herbivores than to plants that are emitting GLVs due to mechanical damage.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nwo.nl/en/research-and-results/research-projects/i/17/8517.html|title=How isomerisation of green leaf volatiles affects plant-insect interactions|last=sitewriter|website=www.nwo.nl|language=en|access-date=2018-11-28}}</ref> In order to determine if plants are capable of recognizing and distinguishing between GLVs, a study was done at University of California Davis where researchers exposed plants to GLVs emitted by a mechanically damaged tomato plant, and to GLVs emitted by a tomato plant that had been damaged by herbivores.<ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Matsui|first=Kenji|last2=Sugimoto|first2=Kohichi|last3=Mano|first3=Jun'ichi|last4=Ozawa|first4=Rika|last5=Takabayashi|first5=Junji|date=2012-04-30|title=Differential Metabolisms of Green Leaf Volatiles in Injured and Intact Parts of a Wounded Leaf Meet Distinct Ecophysiological Requirements|url=https://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0036433|journal=PLoS ONE|language=en|volume=7|issue=4|pages=e36433|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0036433|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3340338|pmid=22558466}}</ref> Researchers observed a difference in the plants reaction, showing an increase in the proteins related to defense mechanisms for the plant exposed to the herbivore GLVs.<ref name=":2" /> This supports the theory that plants are able to distinguish between different GLVs, and react differently depending on which signal they receive.
== Antimicrobial Properties == Other benefits of Green Leaf Volatiles are that at the site of damage, GLVs are released in high concentrations and act as [[antimicrobial]] agents to make the plant more resistant to bacterial or fungal [[Infection|infections]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brilli|first=Federico|last2=Ruuskanen|first2=Taina M.|last3=Schnitzhofer|first3=Ralf|last4=Müller|first4=Markus|last5=Breitenlechner|first5=Martin|last6=Bittner|first6=Vinzenz|last7=Wohlfahrt|first7=Georg|last8=Loreto|first8=Francesco|last9=Hansel|first9=Armin|date=2011-05-26|title=Detection of Plant Volatiles after Leaf Wounding and Darkening by Proton Transfer Reaction “Time-of-Flight” Mass Spectrometry (PTR-TOF)|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3102719/|journal=PLoS ONE|volume=6|issue=5|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0020419|issn=1932-6203|pmc=3102719|pmid=21637822}}</ref>. To study the anti-fungal properties of GLVs, researchers at the University of Arizona influenced how plants expressed HPL, the main [[enzyme]] of GLV synthesis<ref name=":3">{{Cite journal|last=ul Hassan|first=Muhammad Naeem|last2=Zainal|first2=Zamri|last3=Ismail|first3=Ismanizan|date=2015-04-10|title=Green leaf volatiles: biosynthesis, biological functions and their applications in biotechnology|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/full/10.1111/pbi.12368|journal=Plant Biotechnology Journal|language=en|volume=13|issue=6|pages=727–739|doi=10.1111/pbi.12368|issn=1467-7644}}</ref>. Scientists compared the rates of fungal spore growth in HPL over-expressing and HPL silencing mutants to the wild type plants.<ref name=":3" /> Results from the study showed lower rates of fungal growth and higher GLV emissions on the HPL over-expressing mutants, while the HPL silencing mutants showed higher rates of fungal growth and lower GLV emissions, which supports the hypothesis that GLVs have antimicrobial properties.<ref name=":3" />
The antimicrobial properties of GLVs have also been part of an [[evolutionary arms race]] that raise questions for scientists. During an infection, plants emit GLVs to act as microbial agents, but bacteria and viruses have adapted to use these GLVs to their own benefit.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=2006-08-01|title=Crosstalk between abiotic and biotic stress responses: a current view from the points of convergence in the stress signaling networks|url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1369526606000884|journal=Current Opinion in Plant Biology|language=en|volume=9|issue=4|pages=436–442|doi=10.1016/j.pbi.2006.05.014|issn=1369-5266}}</ref> The most common example of this is found in the red raspberry. When the red raspberry plant is infected, the virus influences it to produce more GLVs, which attract the red raspberry aphid.<ref name=":4">{{Cite journal|last=Engelberth|first=Juergen|last2=Alborn|first2=Hans T.|last3=Schmelz|first3=Eric A.|last4=Tumlinson|first4=James H.|date=2004-02-10|title=Airborne signals prime plants against insect herbivore attack|url=http://www.pnas.org/content/101/6/1781|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=101|issue=6|pages=1781–1785|doi=10.1073/pnas.0308037100|issn=0027-8424|pmid=14749516}}</ref> These GLVs cause more aphids to come and to feed on the plant for longer, giving the virus better chances of being ingested and spread more widely.<ref name=":4" /> Researchers are now trying to determine whether under infectious conditions plants emit GLVs for their benefit, or if bacteria and viruses induce the release of these compounds for their own benefit<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dombrowski|first=James E.|last2=Martin|first2=Ruth C.|date=2018-01-29|title=Activation of MAP kinases by green leaf volatiles in grasses|url=https://bmcresnotes.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13104-017-3076-9|journal=BMC Research Notes|language=En|volume=11|issue=1|doi=10.1186/s13104-017-3076-9|issn=1756-0500|pmc=5789745|pmid=29378628}}</ref>. Studies in this area have been inconclusive and contradictory.[[File:LyaseNonenalHemiAc.png|thumb|400 px|center|Pathway for biosynthesis of the GLV [[cis-3-hexenal]] from [[linolenic acid]]. The first step involves formation of the hydroperoxide by the action of a [[lipoxygenase]]. Subsequently a [[hydroperoxide lyase]] induces formation of the hemiacetal, the precursor to a volatile C6 compound.<ref name="Matsui_2006">{{cite journal | vauthors = Matsui K | title = Green leaf volatiles: hydroperoxide lyase pathway of oxylipin metabolism | journal = Current Opinion in Plant Biology | volume = 9 | issue = 3 | pages = 274–80 | year = 2006 | pmid = 16595187 | doi = 10.1016/j.pbi.2006.03.002 }}</ref>]]
